It is true that people hold different views on whether professionals should be restricted to work in their home country where they were educated. Personally, I believe that these professionals should, all things considered, be allowed to work abroad if they choose to.

Some people argue, with good reason, that experts such as doctors, scientists, and engineers should not be allowed to work in another country. This is primarily because the education and training of these experts usually incur a huge cost to the home country, mainly in the form of education subsidies or special training programs -- in other words taxpayer money shouldered by the whole nation. Therefore it is only fair that the beneficiaries of these government-sponsored programs should contribute back to the homeland and not elsewhere. Contrarily, some of the poorest provinces in China remain relatively poor due in large part to brain drain. Moreover, the incoming workers are often met with hostility in the receiving country, seen as there to take jobs away from local professionals.

However, the free flow of labour is an imperative of market economies, so it cannot be stopped if we still wish to enjoy the efficiencies of free markets and globalization. The talents will flourish career-wise in a country that is more conducive to their work. A case in point is the famous Albert Einstein, a German physicist by training but who had made most of his scientific contributions in the US -- contributions to the whole of mankind, including Germany. Another, more recent example is that (I've heard it in the news) some European doctors have moved to China because there are so few patients in Europe with the illness they specialize in; and they can treat in Chinese hospitals in a month what must be years worth of patients in Europe: a much greater contribution to mankind as a whole. Indeed, if we go back to the brain drain example in China, we can see that even the poorer provinces have been growing substantially in absolute terms, thanks to a more optimal use of talents nationwide.

In conclusion, I contend that the overall benefits to humanity is greatest when highly skilled people are allowed to choose the country in which to work.